"In October 2012, a House Intelligence Committee report raised allegations that telecommunications equipment from Shenzhen-based Huawei Technologies might enable China to spy on the US and even disrupt power grids, financial networks or other critical infrastructure. As a result of this effective blacklisting Huawei lost important business from a key market. Since then it has been revealed that the National Security Agency (NSA) persuaded some US technology companies to build ‘backdoors’ into security products, networks and devices to allow easier surveillance by the NSA – raising fears that US technology sales could suffer a similar loss of business from overseas markets. As we move further into the information age, data is increasingly recognised as a precious asset requiring layers of protection and increasingly bound by legislation. Yet, as laws make the transmission of some data an increasingly risky business, revelations of state snooping on cloud-based services have made organisations nervous about where they keep it. James Walker of the CloudEthernet Forum explores how cloud computing can thrive in such an environment."
